This project documents the design and construction of a DIY high-speed RC boat powered by brushless drone motors. The objective was to experiment with low-cost propulsion systems and improvised mechanical fabrication techniques to build a functional remote-controlled water vehicle.

The propulsion system uses two high-RPM (~10,000 RPM) drone brushless motors, each connected to a custom propeller shaft fabricated using bicycle spokes. The propellers were handmade from thin metal sheets that were cut and bent to form blade geometry, allowing experimentation with thrust and efficiency.

The boat hull was constructed using thermocol (expanded polystyrene foam) due to its lightweight and buoyant properties.

Motor control is handled using brushless ESCs (Electronic Speed Controllers) connected to an Arduino Nano, which receives signals from a FlySky RC receiver. Steering is achieved through a servo-based rudder mechanism, allowing directional control of the boat.

This project demonstrates practical concepts in:

DIY propulsion systems

Brushless motor control

ESC interfacing with Arduino

RC receiver signal processing

Mechanical prototyping using simple materials

  
